{{Underline|FFFFFF}}

<div style="background-color:#00000000; margin:1em; padding:5px 110px; border:0px solid #00000000; border-radius: 0px">
<center><span style="font-size:17px;">
'''Phenomenon 15-A,''' best known as '''Everlasting Isolation,''' is a mysterious phenomenon that branches from [[Phenomenon 15|Phenomenon 15,]] albeit with especially rare occurrence. It, unlike Alone, does not make a definitive presence in individual levels, though it is unpredictable when it manifests and puts the affected wanderer at severe mental risk. Wanderers afflicted by '''Everlasting Isolation''' are seemingly placed into their own distinct clone of the Backrooms, entirely devoid of other human beings or entities. While the wanderer is still able to noclip throughout different levels and interact with their environment, escaping the effects of '''Everlasting Isolation''' is a distant dream for those afflicted.
</span></center>

<center><span style="font-size:17px;">
The wanderer's individual clone of the Backrooms only includes levels that would be considered "liminal" by conventional standards. These levels, including [[Level 0|Level 0,]] [[Level 4|Level 4,]] [[Level 21|Level 21,]] etc. are far more difficult to exit individually while in the "isolated" Backrooms, with wanderers only typically moving between levels every 4-5 months. Transition into Phenomenon 15-A is a gradual process that happens over 3-4 hours, with the final stage of separation being the loss of contact with the baseline Backrooms.
</span></center>

<center><span style="font-size:17px;">
Wanderers afflicted by '''Everlasting Isolation''' will experience an exceedingly higher rate of insomnia throughout their time spent in their separate clone of the Backrooms, as all biological processes are paused during the phenomenon's effects. After approximately 48 hours spent affected by '''Everlasting Isolation,''' fatigue acquired from lack of sleep evolves into a sense of hopeless torpidity. Past ~96 hours of '''Everlasting Isolation's''' effects, mental hazards are especially prevalent. Wanderers cannot undergo [[Phenomenon 35|Roth Syndrome]] while under '''Everlasting Isolation.'''
</span></center>

<center><span style="font-size:17px;">
Similarly to [[Phenomenon 15|Phenomenon 15,]] '''Everlasting Isolation's''' "clone" of the Backrooms is known to possess minor differences compared to its true counterpart. Most notably, a variety of additional levels are known to exist within it which cannot be accessed from the true Backrooms; hypothetically, this may be a result of [[Phenomenon 99|Temporary Manifestation]] having a separate trajectory within '''Everlasting Isolation's''' realm. Temporary Manifestation within the isolated Backrooms seems to favor levels which lack a "liminal" aesthetic or contain a visible sky. However, due to the essentially non-existent communication between those afflicted by '''Everlasting Isolation''' and average wanderers, these levels are practically impossible to document, only having [[It's Been a Long Time|rough physical descriptions]] as proof of their existence.
</span></center>

<br><br>

<span style="font-size:23px;font-family: Mate SC;"><center>Yet, the truly horrifying aspect of this phenomenon is; ''we don't know if anyone gets affected by it upon first noclipping into the Backrooms.''</center></span>
</div>

